<h2>Event in May 2019</h2>
A Bora wind event occurred in West Slovenia and North-West Croatia during 13-14 May 2019 (figure 1). The Bora is a northern to north-eastern katabatic wind in the Adriatic Sea.
A katabatic wind is a drainage wind, a wind that carries high-density cold air from a higher elevation down a slope under the force of gravity. Such winds are sometimes also called fall winds. Katabatic winds can rush down elevated slopes at high speeds, and gusts can reach velocities of 140 km/h. There were severe winds with gusts of 150 km/h reported across the Kvarner region of NW Croatia. In exposed areas the reported gusts were even about 180 km/h. The cold humid air interacted strongly with the orography which lead to torrential rain which is notable in Figure 8.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/may2019/13may2019_croatia_gust.png"><img alt="" src="../images/may2019/13may2019_croatia_gust.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: WRF model 13 May 2019 00 UTC +2h forecast. WRF is nested in GFS and has a 0.025 deg horizontal grid. Data are from Meteo Adriatic. Surface windgusts in [m/s] are shown. Note that WRF predicts the wind gusts reasonably well, but does not forecast the extreme values as observed in the open areas.</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for May 2019</h2>
<br><br>
Spring has emerged in May, and in most of middle and southern Europe there were no frost days, with a minimum temperature below zero degrees (figure 2, left). This is quite normal, as the anomaly is almost zero (figure 2, right). In the Alps and in Norway more than 15 frost days occurred. Even for these high altitudes and high latitudes this was unusual, as the anomaly is positive in these regions.
